# Ryla Engineering Rules
# Senior Staff Engineer — Google Standard
# Full reference: CLAUDE.md

---

## 1. CODE STANDARDS

### C# (Google Style + SOLID + Clean Code)
- PascalCase: types, methods, properties. camelCase: locals, parameters. Prefix interfaces with `I`.
- Max method length: 20 lines. Extract immediately if exceeded.
- Use `record` for DTOs and value objects. Avoid mutable classes for data transfer.
- Error propagation: Result pattern only. No exceptions for control flow.
- Async: all the way down. `await` everywhere. **Never** `.Result`, `.Wait()`, `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`.
- DRY: shared validation → `Ryla.Core`. Never duplicate logic across endpoints.

### TypeScript (Strict + Functional)
- `"strict": true` in tsconfig always. `"noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true` always.
- **No `any`**. ESLint `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any: error`. Use `unknown` + narrowing.
- Named exports for everything except Next.js pages/layouts.
- Co-locate feature types. Only truly shared types go in `src/types/`.
- Functional utilities. Classes only when stateful logic requires it.

---

## 2. ARCHITECTURE

### Backend: Hexagonal (Ports & Adapters)
```
HTTP → Ryla.Api [Inbound Adapter] → Ryla.Core [Use Case] → Ryla.Infrastructure [Outbound Adapter]
```
- `Ryla.Core`: ZERO external NuGet dependencies. Pure C# domain + interfaces.
- `Ryla.Api`: HTTP only (routing, serialization, auth). No business logic.
- `Ryla.Infrastructure`: All I/O (Supabase, LINE OA, TikTok Shop, Shopee).
- Dependency rule: `Api → Core ← Infrastructure`. Infrastructure implements Core interfaces.

### Backend: Serverless Optimized (Azure Functions)
- Entry point: `WebApplication.CreateSlimBuilder(args)` — **never** `CreateBuilder`.
- Target cold start: < 200ms via Native AOT.
- Event-driven: `HttpTrigger` for webhooks, `TimerTrigger` for scheduled syncs.
- No large object allocations in hot paths. Use `Span<T>`, `ArrayPool<T>`.

### Frontend: Modular Next.js (App Router + Edge)
- Server Components by default. `"use client"` requires explicit justification.
- Edge Runtime for all API routes and layouts that tolerate it (Global Edge delivery).
- Route groups: `(marketing)` public, `(dashboard)` authenticated.
- No SWR/React Query until `fetch` + cache tags prove insufficient.

---

## 3. NATIVE AOT CONSTRAINTS (.NET 10) — NON-NEGOTIABLE

The following are HARD RULES. Violations fail the AOT CI job.

| Rule | Forbidden | Allowed |
|---|---|---|
| Reflection | `Activator.CreateInstance`, `MethodInfo.Invoke`, `Type.GetProperties()` | Compile-time source gen |
| JSON | `JsonSerializer.Serialize<T>()` without context | `[JsonSerializable]` + `JsonSerializerContext` |
| Dynamic | `dynamic` keyword | Explicit typing |
| Plugins | `Assembly.Load()`, runtime type scanning | Explicit DI registration |
| DI | Convention-based assembly scanning | `services.AddScoped<IFoo, Foo>()` per service |
| Packages | Any NuGet without AOT badge | Verified `IsAotCompatible=true` |
| Trimming | Suppress warnings blindly | `[DynamicallyAccessedMembers]` annotations |

**AOT Validation command (must pass before merge):**
```bash
dotnet publish backend/src/Ryla.Api/Ryla.Api.csproj \
  -r linux-x64 --self-contained /p:PublishAot=true /warnaserror
```

---

## 4. WORKFLOW RULES

### Branching
```
main        ← protected, production-only
develop     ← integration target
  feat/RYLA-{n}-{slug}   ← features
  fix/RYLA-{n}-{slug}    ← bug fixes
  chore/{slug}            ← tooling/ci/docs
```
- Branch from `develop`. PRs target `develop`. `develop → main` via Release PR.

### Commit Messages (Conventional Commits)
```
<type>(<scope>): <imperative subject under 72 chars>

[body in Thai — explain WHY, not what]

[RYLA-{ticket}]
```
Types: `feat` `fix` `chore` `docs` `test` `refactor` `perf` `ci`
Scopes: `api` `core` `infra` `frontend` `supabase` `ci`

### PR Requirements (all required before merge)
- [ ] What / Why / How sections filled
- [ ] AOT Check confirmed (no new reflection)
- [ ] All tests pass
- [ ] Coverage ≥ 80%
- [ ] `dotnet format` clean
- [ ] ESLint 0 warnings
- [ ] New Supabase tables have RLS policies

---

## 5. TESTING STRATEGY (TDD — STRICT)

**Rule: No production code without a failing test.**

### Test Types
| Layer | Project | Scope | Mock |
|---|---|---|---|
| Unit | `Ryla.Core.Tests` | Use case logic | All ports via NSubstitute |
| Unit | `Ryla.Api.Tests` | Endpoints | Ports via NSubstitute |
| Integration | `Ryla.Infrastructure.Tests` | Adapters | Real services / Testcontainers |

### Naming Convention
```
{MethodUnderTest}__{Scenario}__{ExpectedOutcome}
// e.g.: ProcessWebhook__WhenPayloadIsValid__ShouldPublishLineNotification
```

### Tools
- **xUnit** — test framework
- **NSubstitute** — mocking (**never Moq**: uses IL emit, AOT-incompatible)
- **Testcontainers** — for Postgres integration tests
- **Vitest + React Testing Library** — frontend
- **Coverage gate: 80%** minimum, enforced by CI

---

## 6. SECURITY DEFAULTS

- All endpoints: authenticated by default. `[AllowAnonymous]` requires a code comment explaining why.
- Secrets: `IConfiguration` → Azure Key Vault (prod) / `dotnet user-secrets` (dev). **Never hardcoded.**
- Webhooks: signature-verify every payload before processing.
- Supabase: RLS on every table. Application-layer filtering is insufficient alone.

---

## QUICK REFERENCE: File Locations

| What | Where |
|---|---|
| New endpoint | `backend/src/Ryla.Api/Endpoints/` |
| New use case interface | `backend/src/Ryla.Core/Ports/Inbound/` |
| New outbound port | `backend/src/Ryla.Core/Ports/Outbound/` |
| New adapter | `backend/src/Ryla.Infrastructure/Adapters/` |
| JSON type registration | `backend/src/Ryla.Api/Extensions/ServiceCollectionExtensions.cs` |
| DI registration | `backend/src/Ryla.Infrastructure/DependencyInjection.cs` |
| DB migration | `supabase/migrations/` |
| Frontend feature | `frontend/src/app/(dashboard)/` |
| Shared types | `frontend/src/types/` |
